1️⃣ Requirements Breakdown
A. Mandatory
From the subject and expectations:

Networking & I/O
 Listen on multiple ports.

 Support multiple clients concurrently without threads (use poll / select / epoll).

 Non-blocking sockets & proper timeout handling.

 Graceful shutdown on SIGINT/SIGQUIT.

HTTP/1.1 Core
 Parse HTTP requests (method, URI, version, headers, body).

 Support GET, POST, DELETE methods.

 	Correctly handle keep-alive connections.

 	Send proper status codes and headers.

 	Chunked transfer encoding (receive & send).

 	Request size limit.

Static File Serving
 	Serve static files from root directory.

 	Custom error pages.

 	Directory listing (autoindex on/off).

Configuration File
 	Parse .conf file (Nginx-like syntax).

	Multiple server blocks.

 	Per-server and per-location configuration.

 	Root, index, error_page, client_max_body_size, methods allowed, etc.

CGI
 	Execute CGI scripts with fork + execve.

 	Pass correct environment variables.

 	Handle POST/GET data transfer between server and CGI.

B. Bonus
	If you go for the bonus:

 	File upload.

	 Cookies.

 	Multiple HTTP versions.

 	Reverse proxy or load balancing.

 	HTTPS (TLS with OpenSSL).

 	epoll (Linux) / kqueue (BSD/Mac).

 	WebSocket basic support.

2️⃣ Categorizing Responsibilities (Clean Separation)


	Core Components
		ConfigParser
			Reads .conf file.
			Builds internal data structures for server & location configs.

		Server
			Holds listening sockets.
			Accepts new connections.
			Dispatches requests to handlers.

		Connection
			Tracks a single client socket state (reading, parsing, responding).
			Buffers for incoming/outgoing data.

		RequestParser
			Converts raw bytes into structured HTTP request objects.
			Validates and handles chunked data.

		ResponseBuilder
			Takes request + config + filesystem state.
			Generates appropriate HTTP responses.

		CGIHandler
			Sets up environment.
			Runs scripts.
			Collects and returns output.

		EventLoop
			Manages all sockets with poll() or epoll().
			Calls appropriate methods when sockets are readable/writable.

		Logger
			For debugging and request logs.
			Supporting Utilities
			String utilities (trim, split, tolower, etc.)

		HTTP header and status code mapping.

		MIME type detection.

		File I/O helpers.

3️⃣ OOP Design
Use SRP (Single Responsibility Principle) + Dependency Injection for testability.

Example Class Structure:
		class ConfigParser { /* parse and store config */ };
		class ServerManager { /* create and manage multiple Server instances */ };
		class Server { /* listen socket, accept connections */ };
		class Connection { /* read/write buffers, request/response state */ };
		class Request { /* parsed HTTP request */ };
		class Response { /* generated HTTP response */ };
		class RequestParser { /* parse raw data into Request */ };
		class ResponseBuilder { /* build response from Request */ };
		class CGIHandler { /* run CGI scripts */ };
		class EventLoop { /* manage sockets with poll/epoll */ };
		class Logger { /* log to stdout or file */ };

4️⃣ Test-Driven Development (TDD) Plan
Unit Tests (catch bugs early):

		Request parsing (valid/invalid requests).

		Response building (status codes, headers).

		Config parsing.

		CGI execution with mock scripts.

		Integration Tests:

		Make real HTTP requests with curl and compare responses.

		Test concurrency with multiple curl/ab/wrk clients.

		Stress Tests:

		Large files.

		Slowloris-type attacks (send partial requests slowly).

		Many concurrent connections.

		Tools:

		Catch2 / GoogleTest for C++ unit tests.

		Python requests module for integration tests.

5️⃣ Data-Driven Design
		Store server configs in structs/classes loaded from config files.

		Store HTTP methods, status codes, MIME types in maps/dictionaries.

		Make request handling decisions by looking up data, not hardcoding logic.

		Example: std::map<int, std::string> statusMessages;

6️⃣ Plan of Attack (Step-by-Step)

	Phase 1 – Skeleton
		Create ConfigParser → parse .conf file into memory.
		Create ServerManager → listen on configured ports.

	Phase 2 – Basic HTTP
		Implement EventLoop with poll().
		Accept connections, store in Connection objects.
		Implement RequestParser for simple GET requests.
		Implement ResponseBuilder to serve static files.

	Phase 3 – Advanced HTTP
		Add POST & DELETE methods.
		Add directory listing, custom error pages.
		Handle keep-alive and request size limit.
		Implement chunked transfer decoding.

	Phase 4 – CGI
		Implement CGIHandler with fork + execve.
		Pass correct environment vars.
		Integrate CGI into request handling.

	Phase 5 – Hardening
		Properly handle timeouts.
		Handle edge cases (malformed requests, large bodies).
		Logging.

	Phase 6 – Bonus
		File upload.
		Cookies/session handling.

TLS.

